The interface is designed for user interaction with various fields such as checkboxes (for multiple-choice answers), text input fields, and radio buttons (also for multiple-choice answers). There are also sections where users can select from dropdown menus.

At the top of the image, there's a header that reads "Instructions" followed by some instructions in English. The survey includes questions about trust coverage, mood impact, age, employment status, and other demographic information. It also asks about the time spent watching Olympics content daily, satisfaction with the country's Olympic performance, likelihood of following the next Olympics, favorite Olympic moment, and current employment status.

The user is asked to select some options for a question about moving to the next page, which includes an option to move immediately or wait until the end of the survey. The user can also select whether they want to receive updates on the Olympics periodically, how much time they spend daily on Olympic content, and whether they agree with certain statements related to the Olympics.

The bottom part of the image shows a section where users can enter their name or email address for future communication. There's an option to agree with the terms and conditions, which includes a note about spending daily on Olympics content and a question about mood.

At the very bottom of the image, there is a "Next" button indicating that this is part of a multi-step survey where users can move through different pages. The interface also includes a checkbox for agreement with the terms and conditions, which seems to be a common feature in online surveys to ensure that participants have read and understood the terms before proceeding.

The image does not contain any text or content that would require specific action intent instructions, as it is primarily a visual representation of an online survey interface.
